A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that finds its place in the dashboard of each car.
The devices that record every kilometre driven and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state planning offices to revise the outdated system for financing U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and advocate for the government to use the small boxes to record the kilometres driven – and possibly also where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax returns.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of data protection concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s not something we’ll only possibly use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, CEO of Southern California Assn. of Governments, who plans to record the miles driven by all California drivers in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for this is here.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from the taxes, is bankrupting the U.S. taxpayers at the warhead.
In America, however, there is not as much thought as before.
Cars consume less fuel.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per liter) has not increased for 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by one cent at high fuel prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state has recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful option in the long term,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea resonates with urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way that congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
California planners are using the system to develop strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally-announced goals for climate change.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also motivated by the idea of having drivers pay for the distance covered.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, asked Congress to move toward mile-based billing.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million expensive pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
However, the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the advance and thus responded to the concerns of rural MPs representing people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city on a daily basis.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most engaged is Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering this.
Illinois tests it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, drivers were skeptical about the idea that the government could track any of their movements.
“Concerning Big Brother and things like that was a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and profit management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data about the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to capture the miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
So, Khan said, the public would also be calmer.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not start to help states tax drivers.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging car insurance market where drivers are expected to pay based on miles driven.
But the devices tested by it are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded by modem.
“People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Major mistakes were made in some of these public pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose no device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Other agencies hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a tax-paying device that also allows parking fees to be paid, insurance only has to be paid for miles driven, and speed data is collected from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which drivers can avoid traffic jams.
“Automobiles would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system,” the city’s planning document states.
However, some traffic planners wonder whether the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction maneuver.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by increasing fuel taxes.
An additional one-off fee or annual fee could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
“There is no reason for surgery if an aspirin is sufficient,” said Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
