Esa Decides on Large Space Missions: Missions for Billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves, or black holes – European space agency experts now have to agree on two major projects they want to launch in the next few years.
There were 30 suggestions to choose from, five are still in the race.
Far worlds.
More than 1,000 planets at other stars have already been found by astronomers.
Whether there are lives on at least some of them, no one knows.
The selection is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or travel to Earth-like planets and perhaps discover extraterrestrial life?
These questions are currently being asked by the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their program "Cosmic Vision", they are looking for ideas for two large space projects that will make the research a decisive step forward.
The budget for such "L-Missions" is approximately one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were debated, five of which have now come to the narrower election.
Numerous committees are reviewing the proposals, scrutinizing the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Programme Committee.
A total of four major questions have been selected by Esa, on which the missions of the Cosmic Vision program, initiated in 2007, are to find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds – and thus also the formation of planets that orbit these stars – are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In order to answer this question, the Space Telescope "Cheops" will launch in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems will be examined in more detail in our vicinity.
However, the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
Using larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres and thus search for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an indicator of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, should ultimately give an idea of what conditions exist for the emergence of life.
An important role plays the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation it emits with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be investigated by way of example.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the Esa has already approved a mission of the M-Class (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is expected to start in 2017 and monitor the surface and activity of the sun closely.
Of great interest to the researchers are also Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
Esa is the first of the three L-missions of the Cosmic Vision programme.
"Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is set to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is to study the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and to investigate whether the natural laws known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could show physicists the way to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to our common matter, which consists of stars, planets and living things like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies together, and dark energy, through which the expansion of space accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", the Esa has already approved an M-Mission here, the launch of which is planned for 2020.
Using a special telescope, the probe is intended to examine the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time across the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts "E-Lisa", the best chance of obtaining an L-mission permit, has a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists understand changes in the structure of spacetime that Albert Einstein predicted nearly 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, the scientists hope behind the project.
The mission provides a detector consisting of two or three probes, which is stationed in space.
Unlike plants on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that formed during the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four more proposals compete for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is to explore black holes among others, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which is to detect and investigate Earth-like planets.
There have already been proposals for sample reconnaissance from Mars, for exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as for solar physics.
