And one that has come so far in the years that it already resembles a fossil: the first time I heard the “independence means passport control” duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance after the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has come to an end.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
All over the EU, parties are gaining ground that are anti-EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative Party for Germany – founded only this year – was able to garner almost five million votes in the September Bundestag election and effectively expel the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis is a turning point.
Due to the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in conjunction with the compulsory jacket, in which the national economy is forced to stick to the single currency, many people feel that the project Europe has gone too far.
The crisis of the euro has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – that was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has fixed its members on exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to do so.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, Southern Europe can be found with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of Brussels’ “green” energy guidelines – a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays double for electricity and quadrupled for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All of the world’s wage fixings do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is mounting, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France’s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and raise Paris to a level with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has pushed Europe up its own economic policy, which is what the battered French economy is struggling with.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile National Front has just won a decisive by-election and thus referred the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among the white French of the working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency block in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to go beyond: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will rather become something like the “Europe of the (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project, hoping to join the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific region suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of (in the final analysis) small England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which includes telling Berlin and Brussels what they can do.
I suspect that Scotland could run quite well in a looser European alliance, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other, similarly thinking countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing it the same way as Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and has won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and planned) cuts that Labour finance minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition had to answer.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to have a austerity policy imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, according to research.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter is already growing breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and were a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time calming parents – usually that’s not a sign that puberty is about to begin,” Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious displays of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, as well as body odor, show up in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (appearance of the first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
“When the development of breasts begins, it still takes at least two to three years to reach the Menarche,” Kaplowitz, also author of the book “Early puberty in girls: the essential guide to dealing with this common problem.”
Time is the most accurate test as puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually marks the beginning of puberty, but it is “frozen” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, tests may be indicated by an endichronologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatment methods to delay early menstruation and ward off another consequence: the premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for a drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavior problems and girls’ feelings of being different from their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or about how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter was given ten days of her life.
Although there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home scared and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media would be the cause.
Boys come into puberty similar to girls in the past.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported conducting a study in 2001 on girls aged six to nine years, which establishes a link between body fat and entering puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys’ facial and pubic hair grows earlier, the trend towards a full-fledged earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need insurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than thought.
