The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information for the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, causing a smoker to experience no nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice administered nicotine maintained their normal activity level.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken a “time off,” the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
