Pfandh<0xC3><0xA4>user booms in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pawn shop in Singapore’s Bendemeer shopping centre, Janani Amirthalinga swaps a gold bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay for her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house, there’s all my money in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although they earn 3,000 Singapore dollars each month (about 1,730 euros) as an administrative employee and their husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it made its exchange, became the third pawnhouse listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Pending jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawn houses in Singapore require an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, which is just under the 15.4 percent that United Overseas Bank requires, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawn houses offer the advantage that there is no need to verify creditworthiness or proof of income, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region turn to pawn houses after families feel the pressure from rising living costs as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose financial policy in developed economies, families with lower and middle incomes are looking for pawn houses to compensate for the difference in stuttering economies.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor’s growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, described it as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore are estimated to have the highest household debt in Asia relative to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has just come out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing export weakness and a slowdown in consumer demand.
“In the end, this means that given rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” said Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical peaks in gold prices over the past two years have further reinforced the trend towards pledgeing personal items, as people are taking the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items are gold in the city-state’s 200 pawn houses.
People say, “The gold price looks good, let’s pledge Grandma’s gold chain and get back next month.”
The largest Thai pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in its stores over the past few months.
The growth in the pawn business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company finances it with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it received this week with the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have come to the crossfire for high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only fined lower interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly raise the debt.
“Customers do not borrow items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables does not increase household training,” she explains.
The mortgage lending business is increasingly accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use mortgages are in financial trouble.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax’s stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from all walks of life come to us.
“These include wealthy people who borrow something for a business or an investment in the short term, or small businesses that need to bridge bottlenecks in the cash flow,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
