FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in airplanes (but do not have cell phone calls)
Passengers can now listen to their electronic devices for reading, working, playing, music and watching movies from departure to landing, but not by phone, according to the new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depended on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals as well as the equipment storage regulations in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“We could very soon approve the extended use of electronic devices depending on the state of the plan,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers need to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They can only start again when the plane has reached a height of three kilometers and gives the captain the green light.
When entering the landing, passengers must switch them off again and not restart them before the plane has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even at take-off, landing and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft converted for the use of Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Professional Flight Attendant Association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we work closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” Glading said.
To be honest, we are sorry to have to feel like guardians on this issue.
Nevertheless, Internet connections for browsing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data less than three kilometers remained prohibited, the agency explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he publicly had to leave a jet of American Airlines because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked on the flight path.
And heavier devices such as laptops still need to be stowed, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Phone calls during the flight are also prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at launch and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, security expert for national traffic issues on CBS News, said mobile phones would still be considered risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that air transmission can also interfere with transmission masts,” Rosenker said.
A industry advisory committee launched by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri argue that there are no valid security grounds for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, it is said that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the shutdown of the device.
In 1966, the FAA began to restrict the use of electronic devices by air travellers after reports of disruptions to navigation and communication devices by passenger-carried FM radios became known, which at the time represented the latest technology trend.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that electronic interferences do not matter to them.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers for several years when the altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit far less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit only minimal radiation when flipped.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Among the proponents of easing restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to detect problems but could not detect them.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings regarding the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the disruption to the equipment is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there are only occasional reports of pilots speaking for a malfunction of aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to arrange for the switch-off of the devices by passengers in poor visibility when instrument landing.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adjustment for travelers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not contrary to safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
