Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA employees charged with allegations against Jonathan Lord of sexual offences
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) were charged with child sexual offences before allegations were made against child care provider Jonathan Lord from Caringbah in 2011, as the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse learned.
However, in the opening statement before the Commission, the YMCA stated that it had “never been involved in an incident of sexual child abuse in the organization.”
Chief executive Phillip Hare was questioned about a case in which one YMCA employee had been charged with child pornography offences, and another in which a sports teacher at YMCA Caringbah Hall had been convicted of abuse of children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, a lawyer assisting the Commission, that he knew of the first case, but did not know the second.
He admitted that the opening statement of the YMCA to the Commission was also inaccurate in the claim that "there have been external reviews of the YMCA, in which the YMCA has been recognised as at the forefront of child safety".
Instead, evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA has been informed that it has received the second-lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit of the Department of Education and Communities in August of the year.
Hare, who started at the YMCA at 21, admitted that the management had failed “from me down” in Lord’s appointment and did not ensure that employees had been aware of their obligations to report violations of the Child Safety Guidelines.
Lord was convicted at the beginning of the year of sexual misconduct on twelve boys during his two-year tenure at the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare argues, however, that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented employees from reporting Lord’s violations regarding the safety of children.
The staff said they had observed violations, including that Lord was alone with children, privately cared for them as a babysitter, had them sit on his lap, told one that he loved it, and had children play with his cell phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose superior was Lord and who had asked for a child protection training because she was concerned about his behavior, stated that the child service director Jacqui Barnat, who was Lord’s superior at YMCA Caringbah, “was very intimidating and most of the time very unimaginable.”
The Managing Director stated that he would not accept statements from employees that they did not dare to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, rather, their friendship with Lord had impaired their judgment, which is why they had not reported him.
Hare stated that he had informed the Executive Board of YMCA NSW of his view that the lesson the organization had to draw from the “Jonathan Lord Incident” was “not about reporting” by employees, and the Executive Board had agreed to him.
Hare said the decision to urge employees to sign confidentiality obligations shortly after the allegations appeared had been made by the managing director of YMCA’s child services, Liam Whitley.
He said it was intended to prevent contamination of the evidence, but this had been “over-resilient” and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW was not a safe organization for children between 2009 and 2011, said Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, an expert on sexual child abuse, to the Commission.
He explained that there had been “serious problems” in hiring, reviewing, hiring, training and supervising employees.
The hearing was postponed until December 20.
