Scientists were able to shed more light on the relationship between a dog’s tailweaving and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with the tail were more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and react to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres of the brain respond differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just as in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the lateral tailweeds of their peers, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the cock moves in one direction, sometimes in the other
Professor Vallortigara said: “We have shown the dogs films with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (from the perspective of the whirling dog seen), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the inclination of the tail was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog, who wobbles), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs had learned from experience what movements they should be concerned about and when not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and the swinging with the tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behavior and the right side produces a less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their animal’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behavior and guest scholar at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it’s a satisfied dog.
Another research at the University of Victoria in Canada stated: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog if his ‘tail’ is to the left and not to the right, rather than to become restless – just the other way around than in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could therefore be due to the fact that in the various studies the dogs did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
“There is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain halves are used for different purposes, but many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
But since their behavior is easy to record, it probably won’t take long for us to understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
