Pope Francis appoints first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will call for the first time new cardinals of the Catholic Church on February 22, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest-ranking clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope, and they are also the ones who choose a pope, so that Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer participate in the election of the Pope – that is the case for a group of 120 “electoral cardinals”.
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said there would be a meeting of all cardinals before the ceremony to appoint the new cardinals, also known as the Consistory, was held.
“Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the Consistory in February in advance so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from around the world can be planned,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of eligible cardinals is likely to drop by February.
He explained that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as necessary so that the number of eligible cardinals again amounts to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he wants.
The consistory next year is significant because it is the first since the election of Francis in March this year, Valero said.
There is currently a certain overhang on the part of Europe and especially Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals, founded by Francis, to find a group of eight cardinals from all over the world who are tasked with finding opportunities to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything alone.
“Now, Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He explained that it was “well possible” that Francis asked the cardinals for advice.
But so far we have not been in this position – this is all completely new.
Valero said that the bishops would typically be called cardinals from large places, but Pope Francis was “full of surprises – so we don’t know who he is appointing.”
