I have elected President Obama twice in the hope that change is possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by Republican blockade tactics
The blockade policy does not excuse the website problems of Obamacare, the drone attacks
Obama’s memoirs about the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what would have been possible.
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a very sad book.
It’s a book that I believed would cheer me up during the gloomy second year of my medical studies and give me hope again.
It’s called “The Audacity to Win” and describes Barack Obama’s memoirs for the 2008 presidential election.
When I’m done with my patient’s notes in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could take a breath out of a speech.
The election became a landslide victory and news spokesmen stopped to face the historic significance of this hour.
My classmates were crying with joy and my parents were collecting all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries were on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama moved to office in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is an evil awakening, as if being snatched from a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague reminder, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first gave my vote, something has actually changed.
But it's just nothing I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and multifaceted things that Obama has achieved, from the passing of the Affordable Care Act for Health Insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of forced concealment of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that the party-political blockade tactic has tipped too many efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and closing Guantanamo Bay, to name but a few.
