Salem: Johanna Rahner at the Ecumenical Forum
The next Ecumenical Forum on Monday, October 21, in the Neues Museum des Schloss is about the topic "To Hell with Hell - Theological Considerations on Today's Dealing with the Last Things".
The speaker is Professor Johanna Rahner.
The Ecumenical Forum is an initiative of the Catholic and Evangelical Churches of Salem, the Salem Castle and the Bodenseekreis Cultural Office.
Johanna Rahner wants to investigate in the forum how people today classify the "last things" after death.
If the people of the past centuries had known too much about it and had put it on those images of heaven and hell that "still shape our ideas", then the contemporary prophetic teaching of the hopes for perfection is rather characterized by a certain embarrassment or even speechlessness.
“The greater hope has been driven out by religious criticism,” says the speaker.
She has "provided us with so many question marks that the exclamation marks seem to have gone away from us".
Johanna Rahner continues: "But the decisive challenge remains the anger of death."
This is the question of that longing, "which dreams that everything may be good in the end."
Johanna Rahner, born in Baden-Baden in 1962, studied Catholic theology and biology at the Albert-Ludwigs-Universit<0xC3><0xA4>t Freiburg from 1982 to 1989.
She received her doctorate in 1997 as Dr. theol., also in Freiburg.
Habilitation for fundamental theology and ecumenical theology followed in 2003 at the Westphalian Wilhelms University.
Since 2010, Johanna Rahner has held a Chair of Systematic Theology at the Institute of Catholic Theology at the University of Kassel.
