Along the way through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle Brings Free Medical Assistance to Remote Villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 of the 2013 CNN Heroes.
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the Top 10 to choose him as the "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation formed that spread to his brain and there caused a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father in crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
“It’s not easy,” says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five o’clock in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, but you’re not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for 5,000 people each, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
Poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffering in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it mature.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team carried out 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and worked as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels on weekends in rural areas and provides free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people are forced into minibuses and driving on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help with the laced medical equipment.
Not always everything runs smoothly.
More than once, they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will receive like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best lodging the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and Bwelle – with its broad smile and boundless energy – is happy to attend the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team starts investigating hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per trip,” says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document that is required for school but many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the surgery and disinfection equipment is fed by the generator of the group and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early morning hours on Sunday.
It’s a strenuous curriculum, but village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They’re drumming all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then drives back to the city, tired, but proud of the work done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – carried out 700 free surgeries last year and knows that their work makes a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free operation of a fracture he had received now allows him to work again.
“This is changing the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s going to sleep,” says Katie O’Malley, who studies medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and volunteers to join Bwelle’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain hands-on experiences they would never get at home.
“We can be involved in operations where we help to drain blood or keep the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies with them.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and guidance.
“He’s definitely a hero,” says O’Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise he has made to his father gives him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this work,” says Bwelle.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and learn how you can help.
