Tourism: descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, a sewer from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
Those who visit Cologne will not pass the cathedral.
Around 157 meters, the two towers protrude into the sky and make it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who admire the two filigree church towers, suspect that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne’s underworld.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," Schulze says.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted an auto-righteous city, and therefore only what was not too large remained of the remnants of the old city walls.
Most users of the car park therefore also rush past the Roman remains today and leave only their car.
But if you look more closely, an archaeological site separated by metal lattice rods is discovered in the parking deck D2.
You can see about five meters high ruins made of hand plate-sized stones.
“It is the remains of the Roman city wall that was built in the second half of the first century AD,” Schulze says.
Before returning to daylight, Schulze lets the participants at the upper level of the park take a look into a dark, 15 meter deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which unfortunately is hardly noticed.
The next stop of the tour is the pretorium, and here the participants go back down to the depth.
We experience here the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the pretor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means "City of Roman Right and City of Agrippinens, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the emperor's cult".
And the pretorium is the former Palace of Governors, the centre of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the front room of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewer, which is maintained here at about 120 meters in length.
“You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want,” Schulze cheers up the guests.
There's still a surprise for Schulze.
After getting the key at the cash desk, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walkable shaft.
“We are now in the mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater that was essential for the ritual washings.
To this day, in the lower end of the mikwe, whose origins go back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, for which the construction work will soon begin.
However, a few more years will pass until the completion.
