John Kerry, in an unprecedented admission, said the US spying was “inappropriately gone too far”
John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, suggested a wake-up call to the US’s defensive stance regarding its surveillance programs, saying the espionage had “inadequately gone too far” in certain cases.
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, along with Barack Obama, was responsible for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s spying activities became public.
Through the leaked information, the U.S. government has entered a diplomatic storm of disarmament on the part of its allies.
Speaking at the Open Government Conference in London, Kerry said: “Without question, the President and I, as well as others in the government, have learned about some things that have expired almost by autopilot simply because of the ability to do what still dates back to World War II and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, to September 11.”
He then admitted as the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government that U.S. espionage had crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, “In some cases, this has gone too far.”
The president is determined to create clarity, and therefore conducts a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons in this process will not be affected.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force of good and that many lives had been saved through its surveillance operations.
He added: “We are dealing with a new world where people are willing to blow themselves up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is obsessed with killing people, blowing up and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop it before it happened?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people because we have learned about such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to disperse concerns about alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue working with the U.S. in anti-terrorism efforts, as the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he spoke to representatives of the European Parliament and other people this week and was concerned about their threats to no longer engage in anti-terrorism organizations due to frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans remain on board with regard to our joint efforts against terrorism,” Murphy, who is a Democrat for the first time in the Senate and serves as chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
In addition, I am going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, regardless of their anger over the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has collected millions of phone data in Europe have strained relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the intelligence service this week said the reports were inaccurate and based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations cited from documents shared by Snowden, according to which the NSA monitored the phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of national intelligence, James Clapper, defended the spying among allies as necessary and stated that this was common on both sides.
In all the tumult, Murphy said his authority was preparing the trip of Congress to take place this year, and hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other participating members will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact itinerary is still being worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relationships, he also said that there would be some “serious words.”
He said European governments should be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programs they have been using for years.
“We can change our surveillance programmes and thus better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also have to deal with the fact that we are not the only ones spying,” Murphy said.
